Dec. 6th En route
Nadi - Suva by
F1J1 Airlines
4 Engined Heron
Dear F & P! (Fanily and Friends)
My last letter was from Korolevu when we expected to make the
thirty minute flight back to Nadi on the same little Piper Cub which had
taken us to Korolevu but about 11 a.m. the pilot phoned from Suva to report
that his plane was grounded because of mechanical trouble. So we went by
auto and thoroughly
enjoyed the three hour drive along the sea most of the
way, (the road was built be U.S. Marines for deployment of troops to repel
a threatened Japanese Invasion) through little villages and fields of sugar
sugar, makes up about 50% of P1j1 earning with gold
mining 20% and copra another 20%.
Of course the Indian problem is always
present everywhere,
especially in the sugar cane fields and around the
large mill at lautoka. It was to this port that we drove from Korolevu
to spend Sunday night and get ready for our four day cruise starting the
Zollowing morning.
Mostly our preparations were taken up with getting rid
of everything except the few itens we would need on board because we had a
letter from the Captain stating that space was difficult to find. We got
down to two over-night bags and we really didn't need all that we had in
The Cathay Hotel, very modern, kept our suit cases for us until we
The Captain, Trevor Withers, was an old New Zealand Air Forse
wing commander in World War 2 and a great friend of Harold Gatty's. The
wot a pray to to de hot or unt. shies venture we oh, that
project Withers bought a boat back in 1951 and started running cruises down
to the Yasava group of islands scattered more or less in a sixty mile 1ine
starting some forty miles west of Viti Levu, the big island with Nadi at
one end and Suva at the other. The Yasava group was really discovered and
quite well charted by Capt. Bligh when he and 18 others were cast adrift
by the Bounty Mutineers. Bligh did not land his long boat and was chased
twice by large war canoes full of Cannibals looking for a little white meat.
Our cruise was through largely uncharted seas with many small passageways
through the Coral reefs. Our ship, the "Blue Lagoon",
is 50 feet long with
two diesel engines which drive it along about 10 to 15 miles an hour. There
are somewhat cramped quarters for four people in a cabin with upper and
